               <physDesc rend="visible">



                  <p>Parchment codex of the 14th century.</p>



                  <objectDesc form="codex">



                     <supportDesc material="perg">
                        <support>Parchment codex.</support>
                        <extent rend="visible">460 folios (ii+460+i)<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
                              <height>445</height>
                              <width>330</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>315</height>
                              <width>230</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>

                        <foliation>
                           <p>460 folios (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 1 at
                              the end). </p>
                        </foliation>

                        <collation>
                           <p>Extant quires are mostly of 8 leaves each.</p>
                           <p>Quires marked by decorative catchwords on the last page, but only few
                              of them have been preserved. </p>
                        </collation>

                        <condition>
                           <p>Many pages have trimmed margins. </p>
                           <p>Water damage at edges. </p>
                           <p>Finger grease, stains, wax, etc. </p>
                           <p>A few areas of mould mottling. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>

                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="3" ruledLines="29" writtenLines="28">
                           <p>Uniform layout. </p>
                           <p>Visible pricking and page by page plummet ruling. </p>
                           <p>Graphic fillers at the end of the lines. </p>
                           <p>Large square initial words. </p>
                           <p>Last line of text written within ruling. </p>
                           <p>Each of the books of the Pentateuch commences a new leaf and Hafṭarot
                              begin a new column.</p>
                           <p>The beginning of each pericope marked by פ פ פ. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>

                  <handDesc hands="2">
                     <summary>Ashkenazi square script of the 14th century. <name type="person"
                           role="scribe">Shimshon ben Ya῾aḳov Vivant</name>: inscribed as the main
                        scribe in the colophon, folio 460v. <name type="person" role="scribe"
                           >Shelomoh ha-Naḳdan</name>: inscribed as the punctuator in the colophon
                        on folio 460v. </summary>
                     <handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
                  </handDesc>

                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding>
                        <p>Pre-1600. Thick brown leather, blind tooled boards, with bosses.
                           Embroidered velour doublures. Boxed. </p>
                        <p>Spine: Biblia Hebraica. Mus. Brit. Jure Emptionis. 10,455. Plut.</p>
                     </binding>
                 </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>
                     <p>A paper quarto is prefixed to the manuscript, containing a partly Hebrew and
                        partly German letter addressed by the leaders of <name type="place"
                           >Dusseldorf </name>to the community in <name type="place">Essen</name>,
                        asking for help on behalf of the Jews of <name type="place">Lissa</name>,
                        whose houses and possessions were destroyed by fire. The letter is dated the
                        fifth day of week, <date calendar="Hebrew">10 Ṭevet 528</date> (<date
                           calendar="Gregorian">1768</date>). Outside address: Herrn Abraham Moses,
                        vornehmer Handelss Jude in Essen.</p>
                  </accMat>
               </physDesc>



